column6: In this video, we‚Äôll provide an in-depth explanation of Apache Pulsar‚Äôs shared subscription type. Learn more about shared subscriptions here: https://pulsar.apache.org/docs/next/concepts-messaging#subscriptions. Get started with Pulsar today on DataStax Astra Streaming: https://astra.datastax.com/registerstreaming.\\n\\nWe‚Äôre going to look at a feature of Pulsar called shared subscriptions. Typically in Pub/Sub a message topic has only one subscriber. Challenges arise when a flood of messages are published very quickly. That single subscriber can become overwhelmed. A shared subscription type means many consumers can subscribe to the same topic and share the workload of consuming all those messages.\\n\\nDo you have any questions, tips, or ideas about Pulsar subscription types? column6: Apache Pulsar can be deployed on cloud provider-managed Kubernetes services with ease. However, one will quickly realize that the out-of-the-box performance is not optimal for high-volume use cases. This talk won't provide cookbook recipes for tuning Pulsar instead, you will learn a systematic approach to performance tuning. The high-level mental model of the Pulsar write and read path is explained, since this helps to understand what needs to be tuned. The tunable configuration is covered at a high level. Different options for horizontal and vertical scaling of Pulsar deployments are also covered. If you are interested in learning more about Apache Pulsar operations and performance tuning, join Lari Hotari to learn about this fascinating topic.\\n\\n00:00 - Introduction\\n01:23 - Performance Tuning\\n06:41 - Apache Pulsar Kubernetes deployments\\n23:34 - Scaling out and scaling up\\n27:49 - Overview of tunable configuration\\n\\n*This talk was originally done at ApacheCon 2022 by Lari Hotari. column6: DataStax Astra DB uses the Stargate Document API to modify and query data stored as unstructured JSON documents in collections. Because the Document API uses schemaless data, no data modeling is required!  This short demo shows how to use the built in swagger client.\\nYou can get the Javascript 'Collections' client for Astra from NPM ( https://www.npmjs.com/package/@astrajs/collections )\\nTo use the Document API, you must define the namespace that will store collections. Collections store unstructured JSON documents. Documents can themselves hold multiple documents. Multiple collections are contained in a namespace, but a collection cannot be contained in multiple namespaces.\\nOnly namespaces need to specifically created. Collections are specified when a document is inserted.\\n\\n\\nCONNECT WITH DATASTAX\\nSubscribe: http://www.youtube.com/c/datastaxdevs?sub_confirmation=1 \\nTwitter: https://twitter.com/datastaxdevs\\nTwitch: https://www.twitch.tv/datastaxdevs\\n\\nAbout DataStax:\\nDataStax is the company behind the massively scalable, highly available, cloud-native NoSQL data platform built on Apache Cassandra‚Ñ¢. column6: Resources and Step-by-Step for this video on Awesome Astra DB\\nhttps://awesome-astra.github.io/docs/pages/tools/integration/quine.io/\\n\\nWhat's Quine?  Find out in this 5 min demo of an Ethereum fraud tracking example:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z8pXVof9BfE\\n\\n.. or read on!  Some data needs more expressive data modeling in order to derive insights from it.  Graph databases enable richer data modeling with a simpler syntax over relational databases.  Quine has it‚Äôs roots in DARPA research and is the first in-memory streaming graph that supports real-time, event-driven workflows.  It enables high volume, low signal complex event processing like:\\n* Fraud detection\\n* Real-time recommendation engines\\n* Master data management (MDM)\\n* Network and IT operations\\n* Identity and access management (IAM)\\nQuine is a streaming graph capable of building real-time graph insights on streaming data as-is-happens, as well as for the data to be streamed-out for event processing.   The graph data is stored on disk through a configured persistent store with out-of-the-box support for Cassandra or Astra DB. When using Cassandra/Astra, Quine instances can achieve extremely high throughput, high availability, data replication, and failover strategies needed for production operation in the enterprise.\\n\\nCONNECT WITH DATASTAX \\nSubscribe: http://www.youtube.com/c/datastaxdevs?sub_confirmation=1 \\nTwitter: https://twitter.com/datastaxdevs\\nTwitch: https://www.twitch.tv/datastaxdevs\\n\\nCONNECT WITH QUINE.IO\\nQuine on Github: https://github.com/thatdot/quine\\nQuine Slack: https://quine-io.slack.com/join/shared_invite/zt-18zgkbizn-xLHGyB4Edi_C12wyHBhwew#/shared-invite/email\\n\\nAbout DataStax:\\nDataStax is the company behind the massively scalable, highly available, cloud-native NoSQL data platform built on Apache Cassandra‚Ñ¢. column6: In this video, we‚Äôll provide an in-depth explanation of Apache Pulsar‚Äôs failover subscription type. Learn more about failover subscriptions here: https://pulsar.apache.org/docs/next/concepts-messaging#subscriptions. Get started with Pulsar today on DataStax Astra Streaming: https://astra.datastax.com/registerstreaming.\\n\\nWe‚Äôre going to look at a feature of Pulsar called failover subscriptions. Sometimes message consumers get backed up or crash all together. To help guard against that, you can have one or more consumers on standby, waiting to help. Setting the subscription type to failover tells Pulsar that when a primary consumer becomes unresponsive, a secondary should be promoted. \\n\\nDo you have any questions, tips, or ideas about Pulsar subscription types? column6: LIVE FROM HACKING AGENTS ü§ñ‚ú® \\n\\n2024 marked a significant breakthrough in Generative AI, demonstrating that higher accuracy could be achieved by producing more tokens during inference or test-time. This approach, while promising, unveiled new challenges: increased inference costs and slower response times. As we continue to push the boundaries of test-time compute, it's becoming evident that a balance between accuracy and efficiency is crucial for the next phase of AI development: agentic ai.\\n\\nMoving into 2025, agents are poised to take center stage in AI applications, necessitating faster test-time compute on a diverse set of smaller language models (SLMs). Traditional GPU infrastructure is reaching its limits in efficiently supporting and scaling these agentic applications. This is where SambaNova's RDU architecture emerges as a solution, offering a faster and more efficient alternative for deploying Large Language Models (LLMs). This lightning talk will explore how SambaNova is empowering developers to build faster agentic applications, featuring a case study that underscores the critical need for accelerated agent inference in real-world scenarios.\\n\\n\\nAdditional Resources:\\n- DataStax Developer Hub: https://dtsx.io/devhub\\n- DataStax Blog: https://dtsx.io/howto\\n- Try Langflow: https://dtsx.io/trylangflow\\n- Try Astra DB: https://dtsx.io/40kQpI6\\n____________________\\n\\nStay in touch:\\n- Join our Discord Community: https://discord.gg/datastax\\n- Follow us on X: https://x.com/DataStaxDevs\\n\\nChapters:\\n00:00:00 Introduction\\n_________

column6: In this livestream, we explore advanced techniques for improving RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) performance, focusing on the nuances between similarity and relevance in AI-driven information retrieval.\\n\\nThis presentation is tailored for:\\n- Developers and researchers working on generative AI projects with RAG\\n- Information retrieval specialists aiming to enhance system accuracy\\n- Software engineers interested in optimizing RAG performance for their applications\\n\\nOur discussion covers the following key areas:\\n\\n1. RAG Fundamentals: An overview of RAG system architecture, emphasizing its text chunk retrieval mechanisms and integration with large language models (LLMs).\\n\\n2. Defining Relevance: An exploration of relevance in the context of RAG, highlighting its crucial role in providing accurate answers to user queries.\\n\\n3. Similarity in Information Retrieval: An examination of semantic search strategies, discussing both their strengths and limitations in identifying pertinent information for AI applications.\\n\\n4. Case Studies: Analysis of real-world scenarios where similarity-based retrieval falls short, and how to address these challenges using advanced techniques.\\n\\n5. Optimization Strategies: A discussion of cutting-edge methods to enhance RAG accuracy, including sub-query generation, entity recognition, and state-of-the-art retrieval models.\\n\\n6. Integrated Approaches: An overview of how RAG can be effectively combined with content-based retrieval and hybrid search methodologies to improve result quality in AI systems.\\n\\nJoin us for an in-depth exploration of RAG systems and their potential for advancing information retrieval in artificial intelligence applications.\\n\\nAdditional Resources:\\n- DataStax Developer Hub: https://datastax.com/devs\\n- DataStax Blog: https://www.datastax.com/blog/technical-how-tos\\n- Langflow: https://langflow.datastax.com\\n- Langflow Open Source Platform: https://bit.ly/4dRiL1E\\n- Text Splitting Techniques: https://medium.com/logspace/text-spli
